ations across Canada, provides an insider’s perspective on the ways these organizations continue to evolve. Through personal interviews with private funders – large and small, long established and newly formed – Pearson describes their strategies and the varied roles they play, whether as convenors, advocates, brokers, or partners.A timely contribution to the current debate on the legitimacy of organized philanthropy in an era of increasing social division and inequality, From Charity to Change makes a compelling case for the valuable role private philanthropy plays in addressing the challenges of our rapidly changing times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCharitieszCanada. 0aEndowmentszCanada. 0aFamily foundationszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Philanthropy & Charity.2bisacsh  aCanadian.  aIndigenous.  aPhilanthropy.  aassets.  aboard.  aclimate.  acollaboration.  acommunication.  acommunity.  acorporate.  adonors.  aendowment.  afamily.  agiving.  agovernment.  agrants.  ahealth.  ainvestment.  alegitimacy.  anonprofit.  apartners.  aphilanthropists.  apolicy.  apoverty.  aregulation.  arelations.  asocial impact.  asocial responsibility.  asocial.  awealth.  aworkforce.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228015598?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228015598423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228015598/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles